{
  "flash_cards": [
    {
      "topic_id": 558,
      "topic_name": "Development of Resources",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 914,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><strong>Agenda 21</strong></p>\n\n<p>An agenda to combat environmental damage, poverty and disease through global co-operation on common interests, mutual needs and shared responsibilities.</p>",
          "order": 914,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 915,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657613714-tktf5c.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 239px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 915,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 916,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Earth Summit was organized in 1992 in Rio de Janeiro in which more than 100 state heads agreed with Agenda 21 for the sustainable development and proper use of resources.</p>",
          "order": 916,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 917,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657708788-qq6yrq.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 124px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 917,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 918,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Resource planning is essential for sustainable existence of all forms of life.</p>",
          "order": 918,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 919,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>An equitable distribution of resources has become essential for a sustained quality of life and global peace.</p>",
          "order": 919,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 920,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657708848-u3khrc.jpg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 242px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 920,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 921,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>It was believed that resources are free gifts of nature. As a result, human beings used them indiscriminately.</p>",
          "order": 921,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 922,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Resources are vital for human survival as well as for maintaining the quality of life.</p>",
          "order": 922,
          "topic_id": 558,
          "topic_name": "Development of Resources"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 559,
      "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 902,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657706317-uf3mge.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 82px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 902,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 903,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Gandhiji thought that exploitative nature of modern technology is the root cause for depletion at global level.</p>",
          "order": 903,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 904,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"142\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657707631-hcrpnz.jpg\" width=\"260\" /></p>",
          "order": 904,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 905,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Overuse of resources creates many socio-economic problems. To overcome these problems, resource conservation at various levels is important. This had been the main concern of the leaders and thinkers in the past.</p>",
          "order": 905,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 906,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>India has made concerted efforts for achieving the goals of resource planning right from the First Five Year Plan launched after Independence.</p>",
          "order": 906,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 907,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>There is a need for balanced resource planning at the national, state, regional and local levels.</p>",
          "order": 907,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 908,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657708424-7vtkqf.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 164px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 908,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 909,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657614265-cn6ncm.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 47px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 909,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 910,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657614059-4xjn38.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 46px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 910,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 911,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657613887-3gtqwv.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 65px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 911,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 912,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Resource planning becomes more important in a country like India, where resources are not distributed properly.</p>",
          "order": 912,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 913,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Planning is the widely accepted strategy for judicious use of resources.</p>",
          "order": 913,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 5305,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657708257-3vwy32.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 178px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 2105,
          "topic_id": 559,
          "topic_name": "Resource Planning in India"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 560,
      "topic_name": "Land Resources",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 897,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657703435-jxtke8.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 284px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 897,
          "topic_id": 560,
          "topic_name": "Land Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 898,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>India has land under a variety of relief features, namely mountains, plateaus, plains and islands.</p>",
          "order": 898,
          "topic_id": 560,
          "topic_name": "Land Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 899,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Land is an asset of a finite magnitude, therefore, it is important to use the available land for various purposes with careful planning.</p>",
          "order": 899,
          "topic_id": 560,
          "topic_name": "Land Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 900,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Land supports natural vegetation, wild life, human life, economic activities, transport and communication systems.</p>",
          "order": 900,
          "topic_id": 560,
          "topic_name": "Land Resources"
        },
        {
          "id": 901,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>We live on land&nbsp;we perform our economic activities on land and we use it in different ways. Thus, land is a natural resource of utmost importance.</p>",
          "order": 901,
          "topic_id": 560,
          "topic_name": "Land Resources"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 561,
      "topic_name": "Land Utilization",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 893,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657618910-n87456.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 69px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 893,
          "topic_id": 561,
          "topic_name": "Land Utilization"
        },
        {
          "id": 894,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657618843-xe4k2v.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 128px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 894,
          "topic_id": 561,
          "topic_name": "Land Utilization"
        },
        {
          "id": 895,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657703350-5zeb3b.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 191px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 895,
          "topic_id": 561,
          "topic_name": "Land Utilization"
        },
        {
          "id": 896,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657703398-2w2nc2.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 127px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 896,
          "topic_id": 561,
          "topic_name": "Land Utilization"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 562,
      "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 881,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Continuous use of land over a long period without taking measures to conserve and manage, degrade them. This has led to serious problem to environment.</p>",
          "order": 881,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 882,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>A large population which is dwelling at the fringe of forest depends upon the forest and its produce, resulting in the reduction of forest area.</p>",
          "order": 882,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 883,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657619435-ajbtm7.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 144px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 883,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 884,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The pattern of net sown area varies widely from state to state. While net sown area is 80% in state like Punjab, it is only 10% in the state of Arunachal Pradesh, Mizoram, Manipur and Andaman and Nicobar Island.</p>",
          "order": 884,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 885,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Land other than fallow land is either of poor quality or too costly to cultivate, these lands are cultivated only once or twice in two or three consecutive years.</p>",
          "order": 885,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 886,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The total net sown area (NSA) is not more than 54% including land other than fallow land.</p>",
          "order": 886,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 887,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The land under permanent pasture is decreasing; this will create the problem for grazing.</p>",
          "order": 887,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 888,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Some areas of Jammu and Kashmir occupied by Pakistan and China has also not been surveyed.</p>",
          "order": 888,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 889,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>In <strong>north eastern state</strong>, Assam is the only state to be fully surveyed for its land use.</p>",
          "order": 889,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 890,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>India&rsquo;s land use data is available only for 93% of the total geographical area because the land use reporting for most of the states has not been done fully.</p>",
          "order": 890,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 891,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Total geographical area of India is 3.28 million sq km.</p>",
          "order": 891,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 892,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657703146-9annmw.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 206px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 892,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        },
        {
          "id": 5304,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657703217-cgxcgq.jpg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 180px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 2120,
          "topic_id": 562,
          "topic_name": "Land Use Pattern in India"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 563,
      "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 872,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Proper management of waste lands, control of mining activities, proper discharge and disposal of industrial effluents and wastes after treatment can reduce land and water degradation in industrial and suburban areas.</p>",
          "order": 872,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 873,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Planting of shelter belts of plants, control on over grazing, stabilisation of sand dunes by growing thorny bushes are some of the methods to check land degradation in arid areas.</p>",
          "order": 873,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 874,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>In recent years, industrial effluents as waste have become a major source of land and water pollution in many parts of the country.</p>",
          "order": 874,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 875,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Mining process retards the process of infiltration of water into the soil after it settles down on the land.</p>",
          "order": 875,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 876,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The mineral processing like grinding of limestone for cement industry and calcite and soapstone for ceramic industry generate huge quantity of dust in the atmosphere.</p>",
          "order": 876,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 877,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%;\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Reasons of Land degradation</strong></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><strong>Reasons</strong></td>\n\t\t\t<td><strong>States</strong></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Deforestation due to mining</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Madhya Pradesh, Odisha</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Overgrazing</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Over Irrigation (due to water logging leading to increase in salinity and alkalinity in the soil.)</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Punjab, Haryana, Western Uttar Pradesh</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>",
          "order": 877,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 878,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Human activities such as deforestation, over grazing, mining and quarrying too have contributed significantly in land degradation.</p>",
          "order": 878,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 879,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Human activities have not only brought about degradation of land but have also aggravated the pace of natural forces to cause damage to land.</p>",
          "order": 879,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        },
        {
          "id": 880,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Ninety-five per cent of our basic needs for food, shelter and clothing are obtained from land.</p>",
          "order": 880,
          "topic_id": 563,
          "topic_name": "Land Degradation and Conservation Measures"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 564,
      "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 865,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>On the basis of the factors responsible for soil formation, colour, thickness, texture, age, chemical and physical properties, the soils of India are classified in different types.</p>",
          "order": 865,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 866,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil also consists of organic (humus) and inorganic materials.<br />\n<img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657620361-5ugqnt.jpg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 334px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 866,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 867,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Chemical and organic changes which take place in the soil are equally important.</p>",
          "order": 867,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 868,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Various forces of nature such as change in temperature, actions of running water, wind and glaciers, activities of decomposers etc. contribute to the formation of soil.</p>",
          "order": 868,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 869,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>It takes millions of years to form soil upto a few cm in depth.</p>",
          "order": 869,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 870,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil is the medium of plant growth and supports different types of living organisms on the earth. The soil is a living system.</p>",
          "order": 870,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 871,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil is the most important renewable natural resource.</p>",
          "order": 871,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        },
        {
          "id": 5303,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657620230-fm7sxh.jpg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 66px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 2145,
          "topic_id": 564,
          "topic_name": "Soil as a Resource"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 565,
      "topic_name": "Classification of Soils",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 832,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Forest soils found in the lower parts of the valleys particularly on the river terraces and alluvial fans are fertile.</p>",
          "order": 832,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 833,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>In the snow-covered areas of Himalayas, forest soils experience denudation and are acidic with low humus content.</p>",
          "order": 833,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 834,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Forest soils are loamy and silty in valley sides and coarse grained in the upper slopes.</p>",
          "order": 834,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 835,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Forest soils are found in the hilly and mountainous areas where sufficient rain forests are available.</p>",
          "order": 835,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 836,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"153\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657621883-p9uhpx.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></p>",
          "order": 836,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 837,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>After proper irrigation arid soils become cultivable as has been in the case of western Rajasthan.</p>",
          "order": 837,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 838,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The lower horizons of the arid soil are occupied by Kankar because of the increasing calcium content downwards. The Kankar layer formations in the bottom horizons restrict the infiltration of water.<br />\n<img height=\"113\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657621785-58g7qv.jpg\" width=\"186\" /></p>",
          "order": 838,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 839,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Due to the dry climate, high temperature, evaporation is faster and arid soil lacks humus and moisture.</p>",
          "order": 839,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 840,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Arid soils range from red to brown in colour. &nbsp;They are generally sandy in texture and saline in nature. In some areas the salt content is very high and common salt is obtained by evaporating the water.</p>",
          "order": 840,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 841,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"134\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657621672-85y7j4.jpg\" width=\"174\" /></p>",
          "order": 841,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 842,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Lateritic soils are mostly deep to very deep, acidic (pH&lt;6.0), generally deficient in plant nutrients.</p>",
          "order": 842,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 843,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Laterite soil has low humus content because decomposers, like bacteria, get destroyed due to high temperature.</p>",
          "order": 843,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 844,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Laterite soil is suitable for cultivation with adequate doses of manures and fertilizers.</p>",
          "order": 844,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 845,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Laterite soil is found in Karnataka, Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Madhya Pradesh, and the hilly areas of Odisha and Assam.</p>",
          "order": 845,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 846,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Laterite soil develops in areas with high temperature and heavy rainfall.</p>",
          "order": 846,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 847,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Laterite has been derived from the Latin word &lsquo;later&rsquo; which means brick.</p>",
          "order": 847,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 848,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"138\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657621462-2rmmst.jpg\" width=\"181\" /></p>",
          "order": 848,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 849,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Red soil develops a reddish colour due to diffusion of iron in crystalline and metamorphic rocks. It looks yellow when it occurs in a hydrated form.</p>",
          "order": 849,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 850,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Yellow and red soils are found in parts of Odisha, Chhattisgarh, southern parts of the middle Ganga plain, and along the piedmont zone (foothill region) of the Western Ghats.</p>",
          "order": 850,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 851,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"82\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657621201-ms8wvw.jpg\" width=\"131\" /><br />\nRed soil develops on crystalline igneous rocks in areas of low rainfall in the eastern and southern parts of the Deccan plateau.</p>",
          "order": 851,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 852,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Black Soils are rich in soil nutrients, such as calcium carbonate, magnesium, potash and lime. These soils are generally poor in phosphoric contents.</p>",
          "order": 852,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 853,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The black soils are made up of extremely fine i.e., clayey material and well-known for their capacity to hold moisture.</p>",
          "order": 853,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 854,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Black Soil covers the plateaus of Maharashtra, Saurashtra, Malwa, Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh and extend in the south east direction along the Godavari and the Krishna valleys.</p>",
          "order": 854,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 855,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Black soil is typical of the Deccan trap (Basalt) region spread over northwest Deccan plateau and is made up of lava flows.</p>",
          "order": 855,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 856,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657702178-arq75m.jpg\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 86px;\" /></p>",
          "order": 856,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 857,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"127\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657620924-n2agf3.jpg\" width=\"167\" /><br />\nBlack soils are black in colour and are also known as regur soils.</p>",
          "order": 857,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 858,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Alluvial soil is rich in potash, phosphoric acid and lime which are ideal for the growth of sugarcane, paddy, wheat and other cereal and pulse crops.</p>",
          "order": 858,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 859,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The bangar soil has higher concentration of kanker than the Khadar. Khadar has more fine particles and is more fertile than the bangar.</p>",
          "order": 859,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 860,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>According to their age alluvial soils can be classified as old alluvial (Bangar) and new alluvial (Khadar).</p>",
          "order": 860,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 861,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Apart from the size of the grains or components, Alluvial soils are also described on the basis of their age: Bangar and Khadar</p>",
          "order": 861,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 862,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The alluvial soil consists of various proportions of sand, silt and clay. As we move inlands towards the river valleys, soil particles appear somewhat bigger in size.</p>",
          "order": 862,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 863,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><img height=\"118\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657620547-eg2pq3.jpg\" width=\"156\" /><br />\nEntire northern plains are made of alluvial soil. Alluvial soil is also found in the eastern coastal plains particularly in the deltas of the Mahanadi, the Godavari, the Krishna and the Kaveri rivers.</p>",
          "order": 863,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        },
        {
          "id": 864,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>India has varied relief features, landforms, climatic realms and vegetation types. These have contributed in the development of various types of soils.</p>",
          "order": 864,
          "topic_id": 565,
          "topic_name": "Classification of Soils"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic_id": 566,
      "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": 820,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><strong>Shelter belts: </strong>Planting lines of trees lead to shelter of crops. Rows of such trees are called shelter belts. These shelter belts have contributed significantly to the stabilisation of sand dunes and in stabilising the desert in western India.<br />\n<img height=\"130\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657623000-vzegnh.jpg\" width=\"193\" /></p>",
          "order": 820,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 821,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><strong>Strip cropping: </strong>Large fields can be divided into strips. Strips of grass are left to grow between the crops. This breaks up the force of the wind. This method is known as strip cropping.<br />\n<img height=\"132\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622899-4rgp5g.jpg\" width=\"270\" /></p>",
          "order": 821,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 822,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><strong>Terrace farming: </strong>Steps can be cut out on the slopes making terraces. Terrace cultivation restricts erosion. Western and central Himalayas have well developed terrace farming.<br />\n<img height=\"112\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622800-yg88qd.jpg\" width=\"242\" /></p>",
          "order": 822,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 823,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p><strong>Contour ploughing:</strong> Ploughing along the contour lines can decelerate the flow of water down the slopes. This is called contour ploughing.<br />\n<img height=\"128\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622721-j23fxz.jpg\" width=\"198\" /></p>",
          "order": 823,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 824,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil erosion is caused due to defective methods of farming. Ploughing in a wrong way i.e. up and down the slope form channels for the quick flow of water leading to soil erosion.</p>",
          "order": 824,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 825,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Wind blows loose soil off flat or sloping land known as wind erosion.<br />\n<img height=\"121\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622596-zt4t8s.jpg\" width=\"176\" /></p>",
          "order": 825,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 826,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Sometimes water flows as a sheet over large areas down a slope. In such cases the top soil is washed away. This is known as sheet erosion.<br />\n<img height=\"101\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622527-z58cqh.jpg\" width=\"206\" /></p>",
          "order": 826,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 827,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The land becomes unfit for cultivation and is known as bad land. In the Chambal basin such lands are called ravines.</p>",
          "order": 827,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 828,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>The running water cuts through the clayey soils and makes deep channels as gullies.<br />\n<img height=\"162\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622451-x9c5rk.jpg\" width=\"220\" /></p>",
          "order": 828,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 829,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil Erosion by Human activities: Deforestation, over-grazing, construction and mining etc., contributes in soil erosion</p>",
          "order": 829,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 830,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Soil Erosion by Natural ways: Wind, glacier and water lead to soil erosion</p>",
          "order": 830,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        },
        {
          "id": 831,
          "flashcard_type": 1,
          "answer": "",
          "text": "<p>Removal of top soil is called soil erosion. The denudation of the soil cover and subsequent washing down is described as soil erosion.<br />\n<img height=\"112\" src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/question_images/1657622053-d2ptrm.jpg\" width=\"179\" /></p>",
          "order": 831,
          "topic_id": 566,
          "topic_name": "Soil Erosion and Soil Conservation"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
